,Not Recommended,256030,16584974,"Posted: 21 June, 2015",all,MasterOfLazyness,"I wanted to like this game so badly but can't recommend anyone buy it.I loved the look, the UI and the idea of having two worlds to mingle in. Twice the fun, right?Two worlds, 1 ShadowNot really. The two worlds thing is nice in theory, but it ends up being a chore. I have to wander around an area as 1 dude then wander around as the other. Sure, it's not that bad and I could easily deal with it by switching it up while I'm still in the same area, right? Both sets of characters take FOREVER to get around. They're far too slow in general. Later on I unlocked an Archer type dude who was ever so slightly faster and it still took far too long to wander around. This is an Action, Hack'n'Slash, right? You know, ARPG like Diablo? It sure doesn't feel or act that way. I literally looked around for a Diablo 2 style Sprint button or toggle; didn't find one. If you're not going to give us the means to move faster then at least make the characters FAST themselves, geez.Hows the Voice Acting?The voice acting is grand! It's great to hear everything instead of having to read literally everything. Sadly, the sound mixing is terrible. Voices either cut off other voices or are automatically played right after the next even if you heard it mutiple times already. There is large amount of NPC's that only have a single thing to say. Some voice volumes are unbalanced and are often too loud when compared to voicing before it or during. For example, I was talking to Morphew and there was constantly a weird busy market place sound effect that contains some yelling that would continue to pop up as he was speaking forcing me to read the text instead of hearing the lovely voice acting.Hows the rest of the sound?Annoying as heck! Just playing the very beginning-ish area with the Shadow guy and hearing the Soul sound effect over and over at the exact same volume each time without any fading or canceling, was like nails on a chalkboard. Then you have mutiple enemies all playing the same loud dying sound effect as well, over and over again everytime. It reminded me of bad Tablet games where they just let the sound effects cut in and out without any control or balance but it wasn't enough to abandon ship just yet. The only good thing sound wise was the music and how it would change based on what world you're in.Cut Scene VideosI have no idea what's going on with them but they look to be pre-recorded poorly rendered videos and watching them on my large monitor felt as if I was rubbing the screen with my eyeballs. Crazy pixelation and overall poor quality.Is there anything else ""good""?Believe it or not, the story. I was more invested in the story of who is the Hooded Man, what happened to Kalig and overall my evil shadowy self then I ever was in Diablo 3. There also a few quests that seemed entirely optional and gave a worth while reward at the end of it. However, the ""search for intel"" related quests were utterly terrible pieces of nonsense. It went on for too long and the quest markers kind of broke during it. The UI is also very good in most areas. The inventory UI seems a tad large and in your face for my liking but at least it was easy to be effective with it. I could tell it was really trying to have only a single window for shops, inventory and character equipped items.Bugs and GlitchesYeah, it should be noted that there are some bugs and glitches. Some areas that look walkable aren't or the pathing is off. Some times an enemy can sit in an area where you're not able to walk towards and thus cannot attack them. Often the screen seems to have visual tears even with V-Sync on and having tweaked the settings.What made me quit out?I ignored everything else mentioned above in order to play the game and see what it had to offer. Again, keeping in mind that I really wanted to enjoy and love the game.The combat is what killed it for me. Besides the fact that the game thought shoving me onto a level 19 character with a bunch of skills that I didn't know what any of them did was a good idea when It wasn't... I could never get past the strange disconnection from the characters. Every attack feels as if it's turn based instead of an ARPG. I walk over to get in range and stand there spamming the attack button, waiting for the attack animation to start up and then attempt to hit them until X target dies. It annoys me how long it takes between each attack and that movement is obviously slow for only you as enemies can zip around while you're still starting up your attack. In short, it's mind numbingly slow. I used the Shadow guy and Kalig, both felt the same. Both had the same issue. Only Kalig had it worse. His attack animation is so long that it could easily be canceled out of. No damage is done to your target when this happens. It makes the fact that you can MISS even more annoying.Even just breaking a bunch of Urns and Barrels takes far too long. The slow nature of attacking makes everything related to it a chore or a test of will. Skills? Nah, they're just as slow and awkward. Skills and normal attacks can hit targets that should clearly be out of range. Some times your first skill as quite the long cooldown making combat entirely about single targeting every enemy.The combat is so slow nothing I do with skills feels rewarding. There is no satisfaction from using an AoE skill to kill off a number of enemies as I have to wait to do anything at all times."
